Feature Selection IP

Defining the Question?

Specifying the Question

You are a Data analyst at Carrefour Kenya and are currently undertaking a project that will inform the marketing department on the most relevant marketing strategies that will result in the highest no. of sales (total price including tax)

Perform Feature Selection.

Defining the metrics of success

Perform data cleaning, Exploratory data analysis and Feature Selection effectively in R

Understanding the Context

Feature selection helps selection select the important features in a dataset. This helps businesses know which features to put more importance on and how they affect their businesses. Feature selection also help reduce features needed for analysis.

Recording the Experimental Design

  • Reading the Data
  • Checking the Data
  • Tidying the Data
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Performing Feature Selection

Data Relevance

The dataset provided was relevant for the objective we set for our project.

Observations

  • The branch with the most customers was Branch A.
  • Most customers were members and others normal customers.
  • Most customers were females compared to males.
  • Fashion accessories were the most bought products.
  • Most customers payed using Ewallets.
  • Most customers bought 1 - 2 items per sale.
  • Most items had taxes ranging from 0 - 15.
  • Most items had cogs between 0 - 200.
  • Most customers rated 4.
  • Tax, Cogs, and Total are highly correlated according to the correlation matrix.

Implementing the Solution

Feature Selection

Filter Method

# Creating a numeric only dataset
sp = sup[, c(6,7,8,12,14:16)]
head(sp)
##   Unit.price Quantity     Tax   cogs gross.income Rating    Total
## 1      74.69        7 26.1415 522.83      26.1415    9.1 548.9715
## 2      15.28        5  3.8200  76.40       3.8200    9.6  80.2200
## 3      46.33        7 16.2155 324.31      16.2155    7.4 340.5255
## 4      58.22        8 23.2880 465.76      23.2880    8.4 489.0480
## 5      86.31        7 30.2085 604.17      30.2085    5.3 634.3785
## 6      85.39        7 29.8865 597.73      29.8865    4.1 627.6165
# Loading the required libraries
#
library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
library(corrplot)

# Getting the correlations of the variables.
#
correlationMatrix <- cor(sp)
# Find attributes that are highly correlated
#
hc <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.75)

# Showing the highly correlated attributes
#
names(sp[,hc])
## [1] "cogs"  "Total" "Tax"
# Removing Redundant Features
# 
sp2<-sp[-hc]

# Performing our graphical comparison
# 
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
corrplot(correlationMatrix, order = "hclust")
corrplot(cor(sp2), order = "hclust")

Embedded Method

# Loading the required library
#
library(wskm)
## Loading required package: latticeExtra
## 
## Attaching package: 'latticeExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     layer
## Loading required package: fpc
# Creating a model
#
set.seed(2)
model <- ewkm(sp, 3, lambda=2, maxiter=1000)
# Loading the required library
#
library("cluster")

# Cluster Plot against 1st and 2nd principal components
#
clusplot(sp, model$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE, labels=3, lines=1, main='Cluster Analysis for Sales')

# Getting the weights in percentages
round(model$weights*100,2)
##   Unit.price Quantity Tax cogs gross.income Rating Total
## 1          0        0  50    0           50   0.00     0
## 2          0        0   0    0            0  99.99     0
## 3          0        0  50    0           50   0.00     0

Wrapper Method

# Loading the required libraries
#
library(clustvarsel)
## Loading required package: mclust
## Package 'mclust' version 5.4.7
## Type 'citation("mclust")' for citing this R package in publications.
## Package 'clustvarsel' version 2.3.4
## Type 'citation("clustvarsel")' for citing this R package in publications.
library(mclust)

# Performing sequential forward headlong search
#
out = clustvarsel(sp, G = 1:5, search = c("headlong"))
out
## ------------------------------------------------------ 
## Variable selection for Gaussian model-based clustering
## Headlong (forward/backward) search
## ------------------------------------------------------ 
## 
##  Variable proposed Type of step   BICclust Model G     BICdiff Decision
##                Tax          Add  -7382.354     V 4    389.0238 Accepted
##       gross.income          Add  55575.522   VEV 3   2961.1245 Accepted
##             Rating          Add -15921.695   VVI 5 -67563.5280 Rejected
##                Tax       Remove  -7383.226     V 4   2961.9966 Rejected
## 
## Selected subset: Tax, gross.income
# Building the clustering model
#
sp_sub = sp[,out$subset]
mod = Mclust(sp_sub, G = 1:5)
summary(mod)
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## Gaussian finite mixture model fitted by EM algorithm 
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## 
## Mclust VEV (ellipsoidal, equal shape) model with 2 components: 
## 
##  log-likelihood    n df      BIC      ICL
##        27364.17 1000 10 54659.26 54524.45
## 
## Clustering table:
##   1   2 
## 564 436
# Plotting the model
#
plot(mod,c("classification"))
## Warning in sqrt(rev(sort(ev$values))): NaNs produced

Observations

  • From Filter method we can see that tax, cogs, and total are highly correlated and therefore should be removed.
  • From the Wrapper method tax and gross income are selected to be added and the other variables rejected.

Recommendations

From the analysis the following recommendations can be made the filter method is the best to use for feature selection since it removes features which are highly correlated. Tax and gross income are the best feature to consider in our dataset when doing analysis.
